        <p>The African Grey market attracts scammers precisely because the birds are valuable and demand is high. The single most common fraud is a too-good-to-be-true price — a "$400 African Grey" or a "free rehome, just pay shipping" listing — paired with untraceable payment (Zelle, Cash App, gift cards) and stolen photos lifted from real breeders. Once the deposit is sent, the seller disappears.</p>
        <p>A legitimate, documented breeder looks different in ways you can verify before you pay. We hold a real <strong>USDA Animal Welfare Act</strong> license you can check, our birds carry <strong>CITES Appendix I</strong> captive-bred paperwork, and we will get on a live video call to show you your specific bird on demand. Reversible payment methods, a verifiable physical location in Midland, Texas, and a written health guarantee are not extras — they are the baseline of a real breeder. If a seller can't or won't provide them, walk away.</p>
