  <!-- 12. African Grey History & Origin -->
  <section id="history" class="py-16 px-4 scroll-mt-20">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-clay font-sora text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">The Species</p>
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-5">A Short History of the African Grey Parrot</h2>
      <div class="prose-cag space-y-4 text-stone-600 leading-relaxed" style="max-width:70ch;">
        <p>The African Grey is native to the equatorial rainforests of <strong>West and Central Africa</strong> — across the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the Republic of the Congo, Cameroon, Gabon, Nigeria, Ghana, and the Ivory Coast. The larger <em>Psittacus erithacus</em> (Congo) and the smaller <em>Psittacus timneh</em> (Timneh) are the two recognized subspecies.</p>
        <p>The species earned its reputation through science. The most famous African Grey, <strong>Alex</strong>, worked with animal cognition researcher <strong>Dr. Irene Pepperberg</strong> for thirty years and demonstrated an understanding of numbers, colors, shapes, and the concept of zero — reshaping how researchers think about avian intelligence.</p>
        <p>That same intelligence made wild African Greys a target. In 2017, both subspecies were uplisted from <strong>CITES Appendix II to Appendix I</strong> — the highest level of international protection — to restrict commercial trade and protect wild populations from rampant poaching and habitat loss. That is exactly why ethical, <strong>captive-bred</strong> sourcing matters: every bird we place is hatched and hand-raised in the United States, never taken from the wild, and documented from egg to airport.</p>
        <p>In the wild, Greys are highly social, gathering in large communal flocks that roost together and forage at the tops of rainforest trees on palm nuts, seeds, and fruit. They are strong, direct fliers and famously wary — traits that, in a home, translate into a bird that is observant, cautious with strangers, and intensely loyal once it trusts you. Understanding that wild psychology is the difference between an owner who is frustrated by a "moody" parrot and one who reads their bird correctly.</p>
        <p>Organizations such as the <strong>World Parrot Trust</strong>, <strong>BirdLife International</strong>, and the <strong>Cornell Lab of Ornithology</strong> continue to document the species' decline in the wild and the importance of responsible, captive breeding. Choosing a documented, U.S. captive-bred bird is not just safer for you as a buyer — it is the ethical choice for the species.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 12b. Intelligence / cognition -->
  <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-clay font-sora text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">The Smartest Companion Parrot</p>
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-5">Just How Intelligent Is an African Grey?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-stone-600 leading-relaxed" style="max-width:70ch;">
        <p>Cognitive scientists frequently compare the African Grey's reasoning ability to that of a four- to six-year-old child. The benchmark for this reputation is <strong>Alex</strong> — the Grey studied for thirty years by <strong>Dr. Irene Pepperberg</strong> at the University of Arizona and Brandeis. Alex learned more than 100 labels for objects, colors, shapes, and materials; could count to six; understood the concepts of "same" and "different"; and grasped a zero-like concept of absence — abilities once thought unique to primates.</p>
        <p>For an owner, that intelligence shows up everywhere: a Grey that uses words in the right context, anticipates your routine, solves foraging puzzles, and invents its own games. It is also why Greys need genuine mental work. Rotated foraging toys, training sessions, and daily conversation aren't luxuries — they are how you prevent the boredom that leads to feather-plucking. A well-engaged African Grey is one of the most rewarding companion animals on earth; an under-stimulated one is unhappy. We raise ours with early socialization and enrichment so they arrive curious, confident, and ready to learn.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

